<p style="text-align:justify;">adorn their caps with a small plate of lead or pewter for every Bear they have slain &#8211; the flesh of this animal is considered the greatest delicacy on earth, and is their usual repast on all great festivals: On these occasions they likewise indulge themselves with brandy; and never think themselves so completely happy as when they can enjoy a pipe of Tobacco.  They boil and eat moss; of which they also make a soft, easy, and commodious bed for their new-born Infants.  In summer the dress of the men consists of a long coat of coarse cloth, extending to the middle of the leg, and girded round the waist with a belt; annexed to which are a knife, a pouch, containing flints, matches and Tobacco with other necessaries; the girdle itself being decorated with brass rings and chains.  Their caps are made of the skins of the Lune with the feathers on &#8211; they are fond of red cloth, and cover themselves entirely with coarse blankets to keep the</p>

